{"title_page": "Zenos Frudakis", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Zenos Frudakis\n| image         = Zenos_Frudakis_Frederick_Law_Olmsted.jpg\n| caption       = Zenos Frudakis working on his sculpture of Frederick Law Olmsted.\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth year and age|1951}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Francisco]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| nationality   = [[American nationality law|American]]\n| field         = [[Sculpture]]\n| training      = [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]];  [[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| movement      = \n| works  = ''Freedom Sculpture'', ''[[United States Air Force Memorial]] Honor Guard'', ''Knowledge is Power'', ''Payne Stewart'' at Pinehurst Golf Course\n}}\n'''Zenos Frudakis''' (born 1951) is an American [[sculptors|sculptor]] whose subjects include portraits of living and historical individuals and poetic/philosophical sculpture. He lives and works near [[Philadelphia]]. His works include those at [[Brookgreen Gardens]],<ref>Robin R. Salmon, ''Brookgreen Gardens Sculpture'' (Brookgreen Gardens, 1993), v. 2, pp. 188-91.</ref> the [[Lotos Club]] of New York City,<ref name=\"The Lotos Experience 1995 pp. 34-35\">''The Lotos Experience, The Tradition Continues'' (Lotos Club, 1995), pp. 34-35.</ref> the Utsukushi ga-hara Open Air Museum in [[Japan]],<ref>''Third Rodin Grand Prize Exhibit, The Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum,'' Hakone Open Air Museum, Embassies of Greece, Spain, United Kingdom and British Consul, United States, West Germany, 1990, pp. 27-28.</ref> the [[National Academy of Design]],<ref>When an artist is voted into membership in the National Academy the Academy accepts a work of art from that artist; Frudakis's work was ''Sheila'', a life-size bronze bust.</ref> and the [[U.S. Embassy]] in [[Pretoria]], [[South Africa]]<ref>Gene Freedman, \"The Unveiling of a Memorial,\" ''USIA World'', April 1989, pp. 10-11. See also \"Hope and Glory,\" ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', Sunday March 12, 1989, cover and pp. 4H-5H; \"Martin Luther King Jr Is Remembered,\" ''Herald International Tribune'', January 17, 1989, front page; and \"Bust of Dr. King,\" ''Washington Post'', January 17, 1989, p. 1.</ref>\n[[File:Freedom Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|650px|left|The Freedom Sculpture with sculptor Zenos Frudakis]]\n[[File:Martin Luther King and Freedom sculpture.jpg|thumb|Martin Luther King and Freedom sculpture]]\n[[File:Reaching sculpture with Zenos Frudakis. Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum, Japan.jpg|thumb|Reaching sculpture with Zenos Frudakis at the Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum in Japan.]]\n\n\n\n== Biography ==\nZenos' father, born in [[Greece]], came to the U.S. as a boy. The oldest of five children growing up in Greek culture, Zenos admired, respected, and was drawn to Greek sculpture. Greek art influenced his aesthetic vision; additional inspiration came from sculptors [[Michelangelo]], [[Gian Lorenzo Bernini|Bernini]], [[Jean-Baptiste Carpeaux|Carpeaux]] and [[Auguste Rodin|Rodin]]. The poetry of [[T. S. Eliot|Eliot]], [[Robert Frost|Frost]], [[Theodore Roethke|Roethke]] and [[Robert Graves|Graves]], is important to Zenos, as is philosophy.\n\n\nBorn in 1951 in [[San Francisco]], Frudakis was raised in [[Wheeling, West Virginia]], and [[Gary, Indiana]], where he worked in the steel mills. He began drawing at a very young age, and in 1972 came to Philadelphia to study at the [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]]. He studied sculpture with two [[Prix de Rome]] winners: his elder brother, sculptor Evangelos Frudakis, and painter James Hanes. At the [[University of Pennsylvania]], he earned bachelor's and master's degrees in Fine Art.<ref>Sarah Blackman, \"Sculpting a Life\" (feature article on Frudakis), ''The Pennsylvania Gazette'', Class of '82, November/December 2002, p. 3.</ref>\n\n\n==International Sculptures==\n* ''[[Reaching (sculpture)|Reaching]]''. Two figures (bronze | 7ft) Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum, [[Japan]]. 3rd Rodin Grand Prize Exhibition, July 20, 1990.<ref>Henry, Jean \"Contemporary Figurative Sculpture,\" ''The National Sculpture Society Celebrates the Figure'' (National Sculpture Society, 1987), pp. 52-53.</ref><ref>{{Cite web| author= The Hakone Open-Air Museum | url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/53f662b0e4b083b394ab3f14/t/55110825e4b03d839644c042/1427179557796/19900124.Reaching.HakoneLetter.jpg | title= \u201cLetter to Zenos Frudakis\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* ''[[Honor Guard]]''. Memorial (bronze | 16ft) Imperial War Museum, Duxford, [[England]]. Dedication 2018.<ref>Imperial War Museum. \u201cMemorial Honor Guard\u201d IWM, Duxford, Cambridgeshire, England.</ref>\n* ''Martin Luther King and Freedom''. Public sculpture (bronze) Peace Garden, University of New South Wales, [[Sydney, Australia]]. Dedication October 19, 2018.<ref>Mavros, Larissa, University of New South Wales, Sydney Newsroom, \u201cBust of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr Joins Gallery of Human Rights Icons at UNSW Sydney\u201d October 19, 2018. Sydney, Australia. </ref>\n* ''[[Lois Browne-Evans|Hon. Dame Lois Browne-Evans]]. Statue (bronze | life-size) Justice Center, Dame Lois Browne Evans Building (Police/Justice Center) [[Hamilton, Bermuda]]. Dedication June 2011.<ref>Aarabdhekivuc, Nadia, The Royal Gazette, \u201cNew Police, Court Building Formally Opened\u201d June 13, 2011. Bermuda. Retrieved 2020-03-29.</ref> \n* ''[[Arnold Palmer]]''. Statue (bronze | over-life-size) Tralee Golf Club, Tralee, County Kerry, [[Ireland]]. Dedication September 10, 2007.<ref>Mavros, Larissa, University of New South Wales, Sydney Newsroom, \u201cBust of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr Joins Gallery of Human Rights Icons at UNSW Sydney\u201d October 19, 2018. Sydney, Australia.</ref>\n* ''[[Constantine Papadakis|Dr. Constantine Papadakis]]''. Drexel University President, Portrait bust (bronze | life size) Town Square, Meskla, [[Greece]]. Dedication July 24, 2010.<ref>DrexelNow, \u201cTown Square in Greece to be Named for Late Drexel President Papadakis\u201d Drexel University, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, July 20, 2010.</ref>\n* ''Lamby (Abigail), Irish Wolfhound''. Bronze (life-size | 12ft x 11ft) Old Bladbean Stud Garden, Canterbury, [[Kent, England]].<ref>Harpur, Marcus, Country Life \u201cWhere Art Imitates Life\u201d p.44-48, UK, August 5, 2015.</ref>\n\n[[File:Payne Stewart by Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|Payne Stewart sculpture at Pinehust by Zenos Frudakis.]]\n[[File:Benjamin Franklin Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|Zenos Frudakis sculpting Benjamin Franklin.]]\n\n\n\n==American Sculptures==\nIn a career spanning over four decades, Frudakis has produced monumental figures such as the [[United States Air Force Memorial]] ''Honor Guard''<ref name=air-force_memorial>Col. Walter Boyne, ''Soaring to Glory, The United States Air Force Memorial'' (for the Air Force Memorial Foundation by the Donning Company, 2007), Chapter 7, \"A Perfect Partnership,\" pp. 80-93. See also \"Guard Honored,\" ''The Academy Spirit'', United States Air Force Academy, Colorado, v. 47, no. 40 (October 5, 2007), p. 1.</ref> installed at the Arlington National Cemetery, and ''Freedom in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.<ref>''Art Business News'', September 2001, front page photograph.</ref>\n\n\n===Monumental Sculptures===\n* ''Freedom Sculpture''. Monument (Bronze | 20ft x 8ft | 7,000lbs) 16th and Vine Streets, [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]. Completed 2000. Dedication June 18, 2001.<ref>Sculpture Review, ''\u201cChanging the American Landscape,\u201d'' Fall 2001, Vol.L, No.3, p.32, [[National Sculpture Society]], [[New York, New York]].</ref>\n* ''[[Honor Guard|U.S. Air Force Memorial Honor Guard]]''. Memorial (Bronze | Monument) [[Arlington National Cemetery]], [[Arlington, Virginia]]. Dedication: October 14, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Air Force District of Washington.  | url=https://www.afdw.af.mil/heritage/ | title= \u201cAir Force Memorial\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''Knowledge is Power''. Monument (Bronze | 8ft x 15ft | 1,500lbs) Over 30 portraits from intellectual history, two 8ft figures free standing. Relief wall portraits: [[Harriet Tubman]], [[Martin Luther King Jr.]], [[Rachel Carson]], [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]], [[Darwin]], [[Albert Einstein]], [[Alan Turing]], [[John Muir]], [[Thoreau]], [[James Hall]]. [[Rowan University]], [[Glassboro, New Jersey]]. Dedication Nov. 21, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Rowan University Libraries, Public Art.  | url=https://publicart.rowan.edu/sculptures/knowledge-is-power-2014/ | title= \u201cKnowledge Is Power\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* ''Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.'', Monument (Bronze portrait bust, granite base / 5ft / 685lbs) Martin Luther King Park, J. Lewis Crozer Library, Chester, Pennsylvania. Dedication November 23, 2010. <ref>{{Cite web| author= Chester City, Chester\u2019s Park System.  | url=https://www.chestercity.com/departments/parks-recreation/chesters-park-system/ | title= Martin Luther King Park |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* ''The Path to Manhood'', Monument (Bronze | Over-life-size) Perot Quadrangle, [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Mark%27s_School_of_Texas  St. Mark\u2019s School of Texas], [[Dallas, Texas]]. <ref>{{Cite web| author= St. Mark\u2019s School of Texas, David W. Dini, Headmaster. | url=https://www.smtexas.org/2016-2017/hmremarks | title= Remarks from the Headmaster |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n\n===Memorials===\n* ''[[Honor Guard|U.S. Air Force Memorial Honor Guard]]''. Memorial (Bronze | Monument) [[Arlington National Cemetery]], [[Arlington, Virginia]]. Dedication: October 14, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Air Force District of Washington.  | url=https://www.afdw.af.mil/heritage/ | title= \u201cAir Force Memorial\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''[[Molly Maguires]] Memorial'' (Bronze | larger-than-life) Molly Maguires Memorial Park, [[Mahanoy City, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: June 21, 2002<ref>{{Cite web| author= Kelly, Joseph Dennis  | url=https://irishamerica.com/2002/02/the-molly-maguires-remembered/ | title= \u201cThe Molly Maguires Remembered\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''The Workers\u2019 Memorial'' (Bronze | 8ft figure, Mayari-r Steel circle, granite base | 2,500 lbs) The Rose Garden, [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]]. Sponsored by 20 unions, 15 non-union industries, 3 cities: Allentown, Bethlehem, Easton Pennsylvania. Dedication: April 28, 1991 <ref>{{Cite web| author= Devlin, Ron, The Morning Call. | url=https://www.mcall.com/news/mc-xpm-1991-04-28-2802053-story.html | title= \u201cSculpture a Memorial to Workers\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''Anthracite Miners\u2019 Memorial''. Relief (Bronze | Left and right panels 6 x 4ft, central panel 8ft sq). Giard Park, [[Shenandoah, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: 1996<ref>{{Cite web| author=The Historical Marker Database | url= https://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=86761 | title=Pennsylvania Athracite Miners Memorial |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''[[Nina Simone]]''. Memorial (Bronze, local stone | 8ft figure) Nina Simone Plaza, [[Tryon, North Carolina]]. Dedication: February 21, 2010.<ref>{{Cite web| author= UNC Libraries, Commemorative Landscapes of North Carolina. | url=https://ncpedia.org/monument/nina-simone-sculpture | title= \u201cNina Simone Sculpture\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''[[Constantine Papadakis | Dr. Constantine \u2018Taki\u2019 Papadakis]].'' Memorial (Bronze | life size). Public Square in Meskla, [[Greece]]. Dedication: July 24, 2010<ref>{{Cite web| author= Drexel University | url =https://drexel.edu/now/archive/2010/July/Town-Square-in-Greece-to-be-Named-for-Late-Drexel-President-Papadakis/ | title=Town Square in Greece to be Named for Late Drexel President Papadakis\n |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''Henry L. Bowden''. Memorial (Bronze bas-relief | over-life-size). Henry L. Bowden Hall, [[Emory University]], [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. Dedication: 1991<ref>{{Cite web| author= Emory University | url =http://www.emoryhistory.emory.edu/facts-figures/places/names/atlanta/bowden-hall.html | title=Henry L. Bowden Hall |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* ''Mr. and Mrs Hillenbrand''. Memorial (Bronze bas-relief | life size). Batesville Memorial Public Library, [[Batesville, Indiana]]. Dedication: 1988.\n* ''Veterans Memorial''. Memorial (Bronze | over-life-size). Henry L. Bowden Hall, [[Emory University]], [[Collegeville, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: 1991\n\n\n===Portrait Statues===\n* ''[[Payne Stewart]]''. Statue (Bronze | over-life-size). [[Pinehurst Resort]], [[Pinehurst, North Carolina]]. Dedication: 2001<ref>Lee Pace, ''The Spirit of Pinehurst'' (Pinehurst Resort, 2007), pp. 86-87. See also ''World Golf Courses'' (Chartwell Books, 2007), pp. 144-45.</ref>\n* '' [[Clarence Darrow]]''. Statue (Bronze | 7ft). the [[Rhea County Courthouse]], [[Dayton, Tennessee]]. Dedication: July 14, 2017. <ref>{{Cite web| author= Fausset, Richard, New York Times | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/14/us/darrow-bryan-dayton-tennessee-scopes-statues.html| title=At Site of Scopes Trial, Darrow Statue Belatedly Joins Bryan\u2019s |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n*''[[Frederick Law Olmsted]]''. Statue (Bronze, stone base | 8ft). Blue Ridge Court, [[The North Carolina Arboretum]], [[Asheville, North Carolina]]. Dedication: April 22, 2015<ref>{{Cite web| author= Citizen Times | url =https://www.citizen-times.com/story/news/local/2015/02/02/arboretum-prepares-olmsted-statue-expected-fall/22738735/ | title=Arboretum prepares for Olmsted statue |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Portrait Busts===\n* ''[[Mark Twain]]''. Bronze, over-life-size sculpture. The Lotos Club, [[New York City|New York]], New York.<ref>\"The Lotos Experience 1995 pp. 34-35\"</ref>\n\n\n\n==Awards==\nFrudakis is a member of the prestigious [[National Sculpture Society]].<ref name=nss_fellow>{{Cite web| author=National Sculpture Society| url=https://nationalsculpture.org/author/zenos_frudakis/| title= Fellows of NSS |accessdate=2012-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Frudakis was invited to participate in Japan's Third Rodin Grand Prize Exhibition, where he won the Hakone Award at Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum.<ref>Third Rodin Grand Prize Exhibit, The Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum, Hakone Open Air Museum, Embassies of Greece, Spain, United Kingdom and British Consul, United States, West Germany, 1990, pp. 27-28.</ref> The Museum purchased a cast of Frudakis's sculpture ''Reaching''.<ref>Donald Reynolds, ''Masters of American Sculpture'' (Abbeville Press, 1993), p. 250.</ref>\n\nIn 1991 he was elected into the [[National Academy of Design]] as an Associate member, and became a full Academician in 1993.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"200\">\n<!-- Deleted image removed: Image:Zenos_Frudakis_Dream_To_Fly_Cherry_Hill.jpg|Dream to Fly, Cherry Hill, NJ -->\nImage:Knowledge is Power.jpg|thumb|Knowledge is Power.\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Gateway_to_Growth_in_progress.JPG|Gateway to Growth (in progress)\nImage:Chef Pep\u00edn, portrait sculpture and sculptor Zenos Frudakis.jpg|Chef Pepin, portrait sculpture and Frudakis\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_General_Yarborough_Fayetteville.JPG|General Yarborough, Airborne & Special Ops Museum, Fayetteville, NC\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Jack_Nicklaus_Louisville.jpg|[[Jack Nicklaus]], Dwight Gahm [[Valhalla Golf Club]], Louisville, KY\nImage:Dwight Eisenhower sculpture by Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|Portrait sculpture of Dwight D. Eisenhower by Zenos Frudakis.\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Mark_Twain_Lotos.jpg|[[Mark Twain]], The [[Lotos Club]], New York, NY\nImage:Nina Simone Statue Tryon, North Carolina.jpg|[[Nina Simone]] in [[Tryon, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"Simone_Malone\">{{cite news |last1=MALONE |first1=GINA |title=Funds sought to pay off Nina Simone statue |url=http://www.goupstate.com/article/NC/20130717/Entertainment/605138687/SJ/ |work=GoUpstate |agency=GATEHOUSE MEDIA, LLC. |publisher=Halifax Media Group |date=17 July 2013 |language=en}}</ref>\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Mike_Schmidt_Philadelphia.jpg|[[Mike Schmidt]], [[Citizens Bank Park]], Philadelphia, PA<ref name=mike_schmidt>{{Cite web|author=Citizens Bank Park|url=http://www.ballparkreviews.com/philly/cit.htm#|title=Citizens Bank Park|accessdate=2012-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Carchidi|first=Sam|year=2004|title=Four legends honored with statues|periodical=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|issue=April 13|pages=F8}}</ref>\nImage:Zenos Frudakis Arnold Palmer Legioner.jpg|thumb|[[Arnold Palmer]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Appelbaum, David, and Mel Thompson, editors. ''World Philosophy''. Vega, 2002, pp.&nbsp;250\u201351.\n* Boyne, Walter J., Rosalie Frudakis, Katherine Jaeger, et al. ''The United States Air Force Memorial Honor Guard, A Sculpture by Zenos Frudakis''. Techni Press, 2007.\n* Dunhoff, Richard, and Philip H. Wagner. ''Philadelphia, A Photographic Portrait.'' Twin Lights Publishers, 2004, p.&nbsp;14.\n* Goode, James M. ''Washington Sculpture.'' Johns Hopkins University Press, 2008.\n* Gordon, Robert, and Tom Burgoyne. ''Movin' On Up''. MidAtlantic Press, 2004, pp.&nbsp;264\u201364.\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.zenosfrudakis.com}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/ZenosFrudakis Zenos Frudakis: Facebook]\n* [https://twitter.com/ZenosFrudakis Zenos Frudakis: Twitter]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frudakis, Zenos}}\n[[Category:American sculptors]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Artists from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:People from Wheeling, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Gary, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Zenos Frudakis\n| image         = Benjamin Franklin Zenos Frudakis.jpg\n| caption       = Zenos Frudakis working on his sculpture of Benjamin Franklin\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth year and age|1951}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Francisco]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| nationality   = [[American nationality law|American]]\n| field         = [[Sculpture]]\n| training      = [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]];  [[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| movement      = \n| works  = ''Freedom Sculpture'', ''[[United States Air Force Memorial]] Honor Guard'', ''Knowledge is Power'', ''Payne Stewart'' at Pinehurst Golf Course\n}}\n'''Zenos Frudakis''' (born 1951) is an American [[sculptors|sculptor]] whose subjects include portraits of living and historical individuals and poetic/philosophical sculpture. He lives and works near [[Philadelphia]]. His works include those at [[Brookgreen Gardens]],<ref>Robin R. Salmon, ''Brookgreen Gardens Sculpture'' (Brookgreen Gardens, 1993), v. 2, pp. 188-91.</ref> the [[Lotos Club]] of New York City,<ref name=\"The Lotos Experience 1995 pp. 34-35\">''The Lotos Experience, The Tradition Continues'' (Lotos Club, 1995), pp. 34-35.</ref> the Utsukushi ga-hara Open Air Museum in [[Japan]],<ref>''Third Rodin Grand Prize Exhibit, The Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum,'' Hakone Open Air Museum, Embassies of Greece, Spain, United Kingdom and British Consul, United States, West Germany, 1990, pp. 27-28.</ref> the [[National Academy of Design]],<ref>When an artist is voted into membership in the National Academy the Academy accepts a work of art from that artist; Frudakis's work was ''Sheila'', a life-size bronze bust.</ref> and the [[U.S. Embassy]] in [[Pretoria]], [[South Africa]]<ref>Gene Freedman, \"The Unveiling of a Memorial,\" ''USIA World'', April 1989, pp. 10-11. See also \"Hope and Glory,\" ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', Sunday March 12, 1989, cover and pp. 4H-5H; \"Martin Luther King Jr Is Remembered,\" ''Herald International Tribune'', January 17, 1989, front page; and \"Bust of Dr. King,\" ''Washington Post'', January 17, 1989, p. 1.</ref>\n[[File:Freedom Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|650px|left|The Freedom Sculpture with sculptor Zenos Frudakis]]\n[[File:Martin Luther King and Freedom sculpture.jpg|thumb|Martin Luther King and Freedom sculpture]]\n[[File:Reaching sculpture with Zenos Frudakis. Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum, Japan.jpg|thumb|Reaching sculpture with Zenos Frudakis at the Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum in Japan.]]\n\n\n\n== Biography ==\nZenos' father, born in [[Greece]], came to the U.S. as a boy. The oldest of five children growing up in Greek culture, Zenos admired, respected, and was drawn to Greek sculpture. Greek art influenced his aesthetic vision; additional inspiration came from sculptors [[Michelangelo]], [[Gian Lorenzo Bernini|Bernini]], [[Jean-Baptiste Carpeaux|Carpeaux]] and [[Auguste Rodin|Rodin]]. The poetry of [[T. S. Eliot|Eliot]], [[Robert Frost|Frost]], [[Theodore Roethke|Roethke]] and [[Robert Graves|Graves]], is important to Zenos, as is philosophy.\n\n\nBorn in 1951 in [[San Francisco]], Frudakis was raised in [[Wheeling, West Virginia]], and [[Gary, Indiana]], where he worked in the steel mills. He began drawing at a very young age, and in 1972 came to Philadelphia to study at the [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]]. He studied sculpture with two [[Prix de Rome]] winners: his elder brother, sculptor Evangelos Frudakis, and painter James Hanes. At the [[University of Pennsylvania]], he earned bachelor's and master's degrees in Fine Art.<ref>Sarah Blackman, \"Sculpting a Life\" (feature article on Frudakis), ''The Pennsylvania Gazette'', Class of '82, November/December 2002, p. 3.</ref>\n\n\n==International Sculptures==\n* ''[[Reaching (sculpture)|Reaching]]''. Two figures (bronze | 7ft) Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum, [[Japan]]. 3rd Rodin Grand Prize Exhibition, July 20, 1990.<ref>Henry, Jean \"Contemporary Figurative Sculpture,\" ''The National Sculpture Society Celebrates the Figure'' (National Sculpture Society, 1987), pp. 52-53.</ref><ref>{{Cite web| author= The Hakone Open-Air Museum | url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/53f662b0e4b083b394ab3f14/t/55110825e4b03d839644c042/1427179557796/19900124.Reaching.HakoneLetter.jpg | title= \u201cLetter to Zenos Frudakis\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* ''[[Honor Guard]]''. Memorial (bronze | 16ft) Imperial War Museum, Duxford, [[England]]. Dedication 2018.<ref>Imperial War Museum. \u201cMemorial Honor Guard\u201d IWM, Duxford, Cambridgeshire, England.</ref>\n* ''Martin Luther King and Freedom''. Public sculpture (bronze) Peace Garden, University of New South Wales, [[Sydney, Australia]]. Dedication October 19, 2018.<ref>Mavros, Larissa, University of New South Wales, Sydney Newsroom, \u201cBust of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr Joins Gallery of Human Rights Icons at UNSW Sydney\u201d October 19, 2018. Sydney, Australia. </ref>\n* ''[[Lois Browne-Evans|Hon. Dame Lois Browne-Evans]]. Statue (bronze | life-size) Justice Center, Dame Lois Browne Evans Building (Police/Justice Center) [[Hamilton, Bermuda]]. Dedication June 2011.<ref>Aarabdhekivuc, Nadia, The Royal Gazette, \u201cNew Police, Court Building Formally Opened\u201d June 13, 2011. Bermuda. Retrieved 2020-03-29.</ref> \n* ''[[Arnold Palmer]]''. Statue (bronze | over-life-size) Tralee Golf Club, Tralee, County Kerry, [[Ireland]]. Dedication September 10, 2007.<ref>Mavros, Larissa, University of New South Wales, Sydney Newsroom, \u201cBust of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr Joins Gallery of Human Rights Icons at UNSW Sydney\u201d October 19, 2018. Sydney, Australia.</ref>\n* ''[[Constantine Papadakis|Dr. Constantine Papadakis]]''. Drexel University President, Portrait bust (bronze | life size) Town Square, Meskla, [[Greece]]. Dedication July 24, 2010.<ref>DrexelNow, \u201cTown Square in Greece to be Named for Late Drexel President Papadakis\u201d Drexel University, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, July 20, 2010.</ref>\n* ''Lamby (Abigail), Irish Wolfhound''. Bronze (life-size | 12ft x 11ft) Old Bladbean Stud Garden, Canterbury, [[Kent, England]].<ref>Harpur, Marcus, Country Life \u201cWhere Art Imitates Life\u201d p.44-48, UK, August 5, 2015.</ref>\n\n[[File:Payne Stewart by Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|Payne Stewart sculpture at Pinehust by Zenos Frudakis.]]\n[[File:Benjamin Franklin Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|Zenos Frudakis sculpting Benjamin Franklin.]]\n\n\n\n==American Sculptures==\nIn a career spanning over four decades, Frudakis has produced monumental figures such as the [[United States Air Force Memorial]] ''Honor Guard''<ref name=air-force_memorial>Col. Walter Boyne, ''Soaring to Glory, The United States Air Force Memorial'' (for the Air Force Memorial Foundation by the Donning Company, 2007), Chapter 7, \"A Perfect Partnership,\" pp. 80-93. See also \"Guard Honored,\" ''The Academy Spirit'', United States Air Force Academy, Colorado, v. 47, no. 40 (October 5, 2007), p. 1.</ref> installed at the Arlington National Cemetery, and ''Freedom in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.<ref>''Art Business News'', September 2001, front page photograph.</ref>\n\n\n===Monumental Sculptures===\n* ''Freedom Sculpture''. Monument (Bronze | 20ft x 8ft | 7,000lbs) 16th and Vine Streets, [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]. Completed 2000. Dedication June 18, 2001.<ref>Sculpture Review, ''\u201cChanging the American Landscape,\u201d'' Fall 2001, Vol.L, No.3, p.32, [[National Sculpture Society]], [[New York, New York]].</ref>\n* ''[[Honor Guard|U.S. Air Force Memorial Honor Guard]]''. Memorial (Bronze | Monument) [[Arlington National Cemetery]], [[Arlington, Virginia]]. Dedication: October 14, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Air Force District of Washington.  | url=https://www.afdw.af.mil/heritage/ | title= \u201cAir Force Memorial\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''Knowledge is Power''. Monument (Bronze | 8ft x 15ft | 1,500lbs) Over 30 portraits from intellectual history, two 8ft figures free standing. Relief wall portraits: [[Harriet Tubman]], [[Martin Luther King Jr.]], [[Rachel Carson]], [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]], [[Darwin]], [[Albert Einstein]], [[Alan Turing]], [[John Muir]], [[Thoreau]], [[James Hall]]. [[Rowan University]], [[Glassboro, New Jersey]]. Dedication Nov. 21, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Rowan University Libraries, Public Art.  | url=https://publicart.rowan.edu/sculptures/knowledge-is-power-2014/ | title= \u201cKnowledge Is Power\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* ''Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.'', Monument (Bronze portrait bust, granite base / 5ft / 685lbs) Martin Luther King Park, J. Lewis Crozer Library, Chester, Pennsylvania. Dedication November 23, 2010. <ref>{{Cite web| author= Chester City, Chester\u2019s Park System.  | url=https://www.chestercity.com/departments/parks-recreation/chesters-park-system/ | title= Martin Luther King Park |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* ''The Path to Manhood'', Monument (Bronze | Over-life-size) Perot Quadrangle, [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Mark%27s_School_of_Texas  St. Mark\u2019s School of Texas], [[Dallas, Texas]]. <ref>{{Cite web| author= St. Mark\u2019s School of Texas, David W. Dini, Headmaster. | url=https://www.smtexas.org/2016-2017/hmremarks | title= Remarks from the Headmaster |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n\n===Memorials===\n* ''[[Honor Guard|U.S. Air Force Memorial Honor Guard]]''. Memorial (Bronze | Monument) [[Arlington National Cemetery]], [[Arlington, Virginia]]. Dedication: October 14, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Air Force District of Washington.  | url=https://www.afdw.af.mil/heritage/ | title= \u201cAir Force Memorial\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''[[Molly Maguires]] Memorial'' (Bronze | larger-than-life) Molly Maguires Memorial Park, [[Mahanoy City, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: June 21, 2002<ref>{{Cite web| author= Kelly, Joseph Dennis  | url=https://irishamerica.com/2002/02/the-molly-maguires-remembered/ | title= \u201cThe Molly Maguires Remembered\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''The Workers\u2019 Memorial'' (Bronze | 8ft figure, Mayari-r Steel circle, granite base | 2,500 lbs) The Rose Garden, [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]]. Sponsored by 20 unions, 15 non-union industries, 3 cities: Allentown, Bethlehem, Easton Pennsylvania. Dedication: April 28, 1991 <ref>{{Cite web| author= Devlin, Ron, The Morning Call. | url=https://www.mcall.com/news/mc-xpm-1991-04-28-2802053-story.html | title= \u201cSculpture a Memorial to Workers\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''Anthracite Miners\u2019 Memorial''. Relief (Bronze | Left and right panels 6 x 4ft, central panel 8ft sq). Giard Park, [[Shenandoah, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: 1996<ref>{{Cite web| author=The Historical Marker Database | url= https://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=86761 | title=Pennsylvania Athracite Miners Memorial |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''[[Nina Simone]]''. Memorial (Bronze, local stone | 8ft figure) Nina Simone Plaza, [[Tryon, North Carolina]]. Dedication: February 21, 2010.<ref>{{Cite web| author= UNC Libraries, Commemorative Landscapes of North Carolina. | url=https://ncpedia.org/monument/nina-simone-sculpture | title= \u201cNina Simone Sculpture\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''[[Constantine Papadakis | Dr. Constantine \u2018Taki\u2019 Papadakis]].'' Memorial (Bronze | life size). Public Square in Meskla, [[Greece]]. Dedication: July 24, 2010<ref>{{Cite web| author= Drexel University | url =https://drexel.edu/now/archive/2010/July/Town-Square-in-Greece-to-be-Named-for-Late-Drexel-President-Papadakis/ | title=Town Square in Greece to be Named for Late Drexel President Papadakis\n |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''Henry L. Bowden''. Memorial (Bronze bas-relief | over-life-size). Henry L. Bowden Hall, [[Emory University]], [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. Dedication: 1991<ref>{{Cite web| author= Emory University | url =http://www.emoryhistory.emory.edu/facts-figures/places/names/atlanta/bowden-hall.html | title=Henry L. Bowden Hall |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* ''Mr. and Mrs Hillenbrand''. Memorial (Bronze bas-relief | life size). Batesville Memorial Public Library, [[Batesville, Indiana]]. Dedication: 1988.\n* ''Veterans Memorial''. Memorial (Bronze | over-life-size). Henry L. Bowden Hall, [[Emory University]], [[Collegeville, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: 1991\n\n\n===Portrait Statues===\n* ''[[Payne Stewart]]''. Statue (Bronze | over-life-size). [[Pinehurst Resort]], [[Pinehurst, North Carolina]]. Dedication: 2001<ref>Lee Pace, ''The Spirit of Pinehurst'' (Pinehurst Resort, 2007), pp. 86-87. See also ''World Golf Courses'' (Chartwell Books, 2007), pp. 144-45.</ref>\n* '' [[Clarence Darrow]]''. Statue (Bronze | 7ft). the [[Rhea County Courthouse]], [[Dayton, Tennessee]]. Dedication: July 14, 2017. <ref>{{Cite web| author= Fausset, Richard, New York Times | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/14/us/darrow-bryan-dayton-tennessee-scopes-statues.html| title=At Site of Scopes Trial, Darrow Statue Belatedly Joins Bryan\u2019s |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n*''[[Frederick Law Olmsted]]''. Statue (Bronze, stone base | 8ft). Blue Ridge Court, [[The North Carolina Arboretum]], [[Asheville, North Carolina]]. Dedication: April 22, 2015<ref>{{Cite web| author= Citizen Times | url =https://www.citizen-times.com/story/news/local/2015/02/02/arboretum-prepares-olmsted-statue-expected-fall/22738735/ | title=Arboretum prepares for Olmsted statue |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Portrait Busts===\n* ''[[Mark Twain]]''. Bronze, over-life-size sculpture. The Lotos Club, [[New York City|New York]], New York.<ref>\"The Lotos Experience 1995 pp. 34-35\"</ref>\n\n\n\n==Awards==\nFrudakis is a member of the prestigious [[National Sculpture Society]].<ref name=nss_fellow>{{Cite web| author=National Sculpture Society| url=https://nationalsculpture.org/author/zenos_frudakis/| title= Fellows of NSS |accessdate=2012-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Frudakis was invited to participate in Japan's Third Rodin Grand Prize Exhibition, where he won the Hakone Award at Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum.<ref>Third Rodin Grand Prize Exhibit, The Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum, Hakone Open Air Museum, Embassies of Greece, Spain, United Kingdom and British Consul, United States, West Germany, 1990, pp. 27-28.</ref> The Museum purchased a cast of Frudakis's sculpture ''Reaching''.<ref>Donald Reynolds, ''Masters of American Sculpture'' (Abbeville Press, 1993), p. 250.</ref>\n\nIn 1991 he was elected into the [[National Academy of Design]] as an Associate member, and became a full Academician in 1993.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"200\">\n<!-- Deleted image removed: Image:Zenos_Frudakis_Dream_To_Fly_Cherry_Hill.jpg|Dream to Fly, Cherry Hill, NJ -->\nImage:Knowledge is Power.jpg|thumb|Knowledge is Power.\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Gateway_to_Growth_in_progress.JPG|Gateway to Growth (in progress)\nImage:Chef Pep\u00edn, portrait sculpture and sculptor Zenos Frudakis.jpg|Chef Pepin, portrait sculpture and Frudakis\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_General_Yarborough_Fayetteville.JPG|General Yarborough, Airborne & Special Ops Museum, Fayetteville, NC\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Jack_Nicklaus_Louisville.jpg|[[Jack Nicklaus]], Dwight Gahm [[Valhalla Golf Club]], Louisville, KY\nImage:Dwight Eisenhower sculpture by Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|Portrait sculpture of Dwight D. Eisenhower by Zenos Frudakis.\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Mark_Twain_Lotos.jpg|[[Mark Twain]], The [[Lotos Club]], New York, NY\nImage:Nina Simone Statue Tryon, North Carolina.jpg|[[Nina Simone]] in [[Tryon, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"Simone_Malone\">{{cite news |last1=MALONE |first1=GINA |title=Funds sought to pay off Nina Simone statue |url=http://www.goupstate.com/article/NC/20130717/Entertainment/605138687/SJ/ |work=GoUpstate |agency=GATEHOUSE MEDIA, LLC. |publisher=Halifax Media Group |date=17 July 2013 |language=en}}</ref>\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Mike_Schmidt_Philadelphia.jpg|[[Mike Schmidt]], [[Citizens Bank Park]], Philadelphia, PA<ref name=mike_schmidt>{{Cite web|author=Citizens Bank Park|url=http://www.ballparkreviews.com/philly/cit.htm#|title=Citizens Bank Park|accessdate=2012-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Carchidi|first=Sam|year=2004|title=Four legends honored with statues|periodical=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|issue=April 13|pages=F8}}</ref>\nImage:Zenos Frudakis Arnold Palmer Legioner.jpg|thumb|[[Arnold Palmer]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Appelbaum, David, and Mel Thompson, editors. ''World Philosophy''. Vega, 2002, pp.&nbsp;250\u201351.\n* Boyne, Walter J., Rosalie Frudakis, Katherine Jaeger, et al. ''The United States Air Force Memorial Honor Guard, A Sculpture by Zenos Frudakis''. Techni Press, 2007.\n* Dunhoff, Richard, and Philip H. Wagner. ''Philadelphia, A Photographic Portrait.'' Twin Lights Publishers, 2004, p.&nbsp;14.\n* Goode, James M. ''Washington Sculpture.'' Johns Hopkins University Press, 2008.\n* Gordon, Robert, and Tom Burgoyne. ''Movin' On Up''. MidAtlantic Press, 2004, pp.&nbsp;264\u201364.\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.zenosfrudakis.com}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/ZenosFrudakis Zenos Frudakis: Facebook]\n* [https://twitter.com/ZenosFrudakis Zenos Frudakis: Twitter]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frudakis, Zenos}}\n[[Category:American sculptors]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Artists from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:People from Wheeling, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Gary, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from California]]\n", "name_user": "Cher Skoubo", "label": "safe", "comment": "updating content", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zenos_Frudakis"}
